        "response": "Let's denote the number of Douglas fir trees as D, the number of ponderosa pine trees as P, and the number of spruce trees as S.\n\nFrom the problem, we have the following information:\n\n1. The company paid an average of $300 for each Douglas fir, $225 for each ponderosa pine, and $200 for each spruce tree.\n2. The total amount paid for the trees is $247,500.\n3. The sum of the number of Douglas fir and ponderosa pine trees equals twice the number of spruce trees plus 550.\n\nWe can translate this information into equations:\n\n(1) 300D + 225P + 200S = 247,500 (This represents the total cost of all the trees.)\n(2) D + P = 2S + 550 (This represents the relationship between the number of trees.)\n\nWe also know that there are a total of 1000 trees:\n\n(3) D + P + S = 1000\n\nNow we have a system of three equations with three unknowns. We can solve this system to find the values of D, P, and S.\n\nFirst, let's use equation (2) to express P in terms of D and S:\n\nP = 2S + 550 - D\n\nNow we can substitute P from this equation into equations (1) and (3):\n\n(1) 300D + 225(2S + 550 - D) + 200S = 247,500\n(3) D + (2S + 550 - D) + S = 1000\n\nLet's simplify these equations:\n\n(1) 300D + 450S + 123,750 - 225D + 200S = 247,500\n(3) D + 2S + 550 - D + S = 1000\n\nSimplify further:\n\n(1) 75D + 650S = 123,750\n(3) 3S = 450\n\nNow, we can solve equation (3) for S:\n\nS = 450 / 3\nS = 150\n\nWith the value of S, we can now substitute it back into the equation P = 2S + 550 - D to find P:\n\nP = 2(150) + 550 - D\nP = 300 + 550 - D\nP = 850 - D\n\nNow we can substitute S and P into equation (1) to find D:\n\n75D + 650(150) = 123,750\n75D + 97,500 = 123,750\n75D = 123,750 - 97,500\n75D = 26,250\nD = 26,250 / 75\nD = 350\n\nNow we have the value of D, and we can find P:\n\nP = 850 - 350\nP = 500\n\nSo, the company bought 350 Douglas fir trees, 500 ponderosa pine trees, and 150 spruce trees."
